      <div class="filter-bar">
        <input type="text" class="search-input" id="dest-search" placeholder="Search destinations...">
        <button class="filter-btn active" data-filter="all">All</button>
        <button class="filter-btn" data-filter="visa-free">Visa-Free</button>
        <button class="filter-btn" data-filter="visa-arrival">On Arrival</button>
        <button class="filter-btn" data-filter="evisa">eVisa</button>
        <button class="filter-btn" data-filter="visa-required">Visa Required</button>
      </div>

      <div class="destinations-grid" id="dest-grid"></div>
    </section>

    <div class="disclaimer">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> Visa requirements change frequently. This tool provides general guidance based on publicly available 2026 data and should not be considered legal advice. Always verify current visa requirements with the destination country's embassy, consulate, or official immigration website before traveling.
    </div>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What does visa-free travel mean?</h3>
        <p>Visa-free travel means you can enter a country without obtaining a visa in advance. You simply show your valid passport at the border and receive an entry stamp. The allowed stay varies by country, typically ranging from 14 to 90 days. Visa-free access depends on your passport nationality and bilateral agreements between countries.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is the difference between visa-free and visa on arrival?</h3>
        <p>Visa-free means no visa is needed at all — you enter with just your passport. Visa on arrival (VOA) means you obtain a visa at the airport or border upon landing, which may involve a fee, a form, and a short wait. Both are convenient compared to applying for a visa in advance, but VOA may require cash payment in local currency and proof of onward travel.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Which passport has the most visa-free countries in 2026?</h3>
        <p>As of 2026, Japanese, Singaporean, and several European passports (France, Germany, Italy, Spain) consistently rank at the top, offering visa-free or visa-on-arrival access to 190+ destinations. South Korean and British passports also rank very highly. Rankings can shift as countries update their visa policies throughout the year.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is an eVisa and how does it work?</h3>
        <p>An eVisa (electronic visa) is a visa you apply for and receive online before traveling. You fill out an application form on the destination country's official portal, upload documents, pay a fee, and receive your visa via email — usually within a few days. You print it or save it on your phone. eVisas are faster and cheaper than traditional embassy visas and are offered by countries like India, Turkey, Australia, Kenya, and many others.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How often do visa policies change?</h3>
        <p>Visa policies can change at any time due to diplomatic agreements, security concerns, or political shifts. Countries may add or remove visa-free access with little notice. It's important to verify current requirements with the destination country's official immigration website or your country's foreign affairs department before booking travel. This tool is updated regularly but should be used as a starting reference, not a legal guarantee.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Related pages -->
    <section>
      <h2>Related Pages</h2>
      <div class="related-grid">
        <a href="/digital-nomad-visa-guide" class="related-card">
          <h3>Digital Nomad Visa Guide</h3>
          <p>Compare remote work visas across 32 countries →</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/packing-list-generator" class="related-card">
          <h3>Packing List Generator</h3>
          <p>Build a customized travel packing checklist →</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/cost-of-living-comparison" class="related-card">
          <h3>Cost of Living Comparison</h3>
          <p>Compare living costs between 40 nomad cities →</p>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

